  'book-mingdynasty':{
    emoji:'📕', eyebrowEn:'History · Read 2024', eyebrowZh:'历史 · 2024年阅读',
    titleEn:'When We Were The Ming Dynasty', titleZh:'《明朝那些事儿》',
    metaEn:[['Rating','★★★★★'],['Author','Dangnian Mingyue (当年明月)'],['Published','2006–2009'],['Volumes','7']],
    metaZh:[['评分','★★★★★'],['作者','当年明月'],['出版','2006–2009'],['册数','7册']],
    ingrEn:[], ingrZh:[],
    stepsEn:[], stepsZh:[],
    notesEn:`If history is a mirror, what it reflects is never merely the alternation of power and the outcome of success or failure, but also the light and dark of human nature and the retention or departure of ideals. What truly touched me in The History of the Ming Dynasty was not the well-known events, but that in the long and complex era, there were still people choosing to persist in something that was almost out of place.
This era is not short of shadows. Wang Zhen\u2019s autocracy, Wei Zhongxian\u2019s manipulation, and Yan Song\u2019s rise and fall clearly show how power erodes human nature and how reality devours principles. But it is precisely against such a backdrop that those faint yet stubborn lights appear all the more touching.
Amidst the turmoil, Wang Yangming sought inwardly and fought against the chaos of the external world with the unity of knowledge and action. Hai Rui clung to his knowledge and almost stubbornly refused to compromise with the world. Zhang Juzheng, on the other hand, chose a more arduous path - being in the midst of the murky current, on the verge of weighing, compromising, and even being almost in the same stream, still attempting to leave room for a more orderly world. Their paths are different, and they may not even be able to agree with each other. But on a deeper level, they are all holding onto the same thing: an obsession with a certain ideal.
Perhaps what history truly leaves behind is not who is smarter or more successful, but who, through the long years of wear and tear, has not completely given up what they believed in. Amidst the shadows of human nature, those unextinguished lights are not dazzling, yet they are tenacious enough.
After reading this series of books, I was no longer obsessed with what history has taught, but rather more willing to believe that even in the most murky times, people can still choose what kind of person they want to be.`, 
    notesZh:`如果说历史是一面镜子，那么它照见的，从来不只是权力的更替与成败的结局，更是人性的明暗与理想的去留。《明朝那些事儿》真正打动我的，并不是那些耳熟能详的事件，而是在漫长而复杂的时代中，依然有人选择坚持某种近乎“不合时宜”的东西。

这个时代并不缺少阴影。王振的专权、魏忠贤的操弄、严嵩的沉浮，让人清楚地看到权力如何侵蚀人性，现实如何吞噬原则。但也正是在这样的背景之下，那些微弱却倔强的光，才显得格外动人。

王阳明在动荡之中向内求索，以“知行合一”对抗外在世界的混乱；海瑞执守其“知”，近乎固执地拒绝与世妥协；张居正则选择另一条更为艰难的路——身处浊流之中，在权衡、妥协甚至近乎同流的边缘，仍试图为一个更有秩序的世界留下可能。他们的路径不同，甚至彼此之间也未必能够相互认同，但在更深的层面上，他们都在守着同一样东西：对某种理想的执念。

也许历史真正留下的，并不是谁更聪明、谁更成功，而是谁在漫长的消磨之中，没有完全放弃自己相信的东西。在人性的阴影之间，那些不肯熄灭的光，并不耀眼，却足够顽强。

读完这套书之后，我反而不再执着于“历史教会了什么”，而是更愿意相信——即使身处最混浊的时代，人依然可以选择成为怎样的人。`
  },
